Exercise 6: Library Management System

## 1. Understanding Search Algorithms

### Linear Search

Linear Search checks each element one by one until the required element is found or the entire list has been searched.

**Characteristics:**

* Simple to implement.
* Works on both sorted and unsorted data.
* Suitable for small datasets.

**Time Complexity:**

* Best Case: O(1)
* Average Case: O(n)
* Worst Case: O(n)

### Binary Search

Binary Search repeatedly divides the search space into two halves until the required element is found.

**Characteristics:**

* Faster than linear search.
* Requires the data to be sorted.
* Suitable for large datasets.

**Time Complexity:**

* Best Case: O(1)
* Average Case: O(log n)
* Worst Case: O(log n)

## 2. Setup

### Book Class

```java
public class Book {
    private int bookId;
    private String title;
    private String author;

    public Book(int bookId, String title, String author) {
        this.bookId = bookId;
        this.title = title;
        this.author = author;
    }

    public int getBookId() {
        return bookId;
    }

    public String getTitle() {
        return title;
    }

    public String getAuthor() {
        return author;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Book ID: " + bookId + ", Title: " + title + ", Author: " + author;
    }
}
```

## 3. Implementation

### Linear Search by Title

```java
public class LinearSearch {
    public static Book search(Book[] books, String title) {
        for (Book book : books) {
            if (book.getTitle().equalsIgnoreCase(title)) {
                return book;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }
}
```

### Binary Search by Title

```java
public class BinarySearch {
    public static Book search(Book[] books, String title) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = books.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            int result = books[mid].getTitle().compareToIgnoreCase(title);

            if (result == 0) {
                return books[mid];
            }

            if (result < 0) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return null;
    }
}
```

### Main Class

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Book[] books = {
            new Book(101, "C Programming", "Dennis Ritchie"),
            new Book(102, "Data Structures", "Mark Allen"),
            new Book(103, "Java Programming", "James Gosling"),
            new Book(104, "Operating Systems", "Galvin"),
            new Book(105, "Python Basics", "Guido Van Rossum")
        };

        Book linearResult = LinearSearch.search(books, "Java Programming");

        System.out.println("Linear Search Result:");
        System.out.println(linearResult);

        Book binaryResult = BinarySearch.search(books, "Java Programming");

        System.out.println("\nBinary Search Result:");
        System.out.println(binaryResult);
    }
}
```

## 4. Analysis

### Time Complexity Comparison

| Algorithm     | Best Case | Average Case | Worst Case |
| ------------- | --------- | ------------ | ---------- |
| Linear Search | O(1)      | O(n)         | O(n)       |
| Binary Search | O(1)      | O(log n)     | O(log n)   |

### Comparison

#### Linear Search

**Advantages:**

1. Easy to implement.
2. Works with unsorted data.
3. Suitable for small datasets.

**Disadvantages:**

1. Slow for large datasets.
2. Requires checking elements sequentially.

#### Binary Search

**Advantages:**

1. Much faster for large datasets.
2. Efficient with sorted data.
3. Requires fewer comparisons.

**Disadvantages:**

1. Data must be sorted before searching.
2. Slightly more complex to implement.

### When to Use Each Algorithm

**Use Linear Search When:**

* The dataset is small.
* Data is unsorted.
* Simplicity is preferred.

**Use Binary Search When:**

* The dataset is large.
* Data is already sorted.
* Fast search performance is required.

## Conclusion

Linear Search is suitable for small or unsorted collections of books, while Binary Search is more efficient for large sorted collections. Since Binary Search has a time complexity of O(log n), it is generally preferred in library management systems that handle a large number of books and require quick search operations.
